I think a lot about the fact that the Millennials were the last generation able to build relationships with artists without being expected to critically examine them.
We grew up in a golden age of media, with a collective consciousness of pop culture that no longer exists.
We could jump into things without thinking about where they came from, because back then it wasn't so easy to determine that.
We didn't have to question the pedestal we put them on. These parasocial relationships were so important and influenced our lives.
That's why we have such a strong nostalgia.
When "The Office" was still on air, my friends and I would order pizza every Thursday and watch the series together.
It was completely different from today's streaming era, where 12 episodes come out all at once and everyone watches whenever they feel like, posting "spoiler warnings" on social media or discussing them in private groups.
Subconsciously, we long for this universal community that used to rule everything.
That's why so many of us still watch series like "The Office" or movies like "Anchorman", which featured so many one-liners that would now be memes.
We've all said these lines, and assumed that most people already understood them.
Today, one cannot even assume that everyone knows something, even if it spreads virally extensively.
There is simply too much, and there is no way to systematize it. Are we even going to get out of this saturation again?
We are trapped in a vicious cycle, constantly discovering new content, only to realize that the artist is greedy or a hypocrite.
Therefore, we must hold on to our nostalgia while simultaneously accepting that the people who created the works we like can also have made major mistakes.
We approach parasocial relationships with greater caution.
We are aware that it is difficult to become rich and powerful without stepping on the feet of one person or another on the way.
Since our collective consciousness regarding media has faded, we have developed a class consciousness that promotes our critical thinking.
There are still those among us who lift someone onto a pedestal, only to be shocked when they fall down.
We are in a phase of upheaval, and I am curious to see where it will ultimately lead.
